{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496414"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1354"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1354"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.57,0.04,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1354"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"574"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42292"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with an urgent request to evaluate a growing lesion on his right nasal bridge. He has a history of regular six-monthly full skin examinations for cancer surveillance. His medical history is significant for multiple squamous cell carcinomas in sun-exposed areas. He does not take any regular medications. The patient reports that this particular lesion appeared three weeks ago. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion on his right nasal bridge is visible (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous cell carcinoma","Keratoacanthoma","Merkel cell carcinoma","Actinic keratosis","Seborrhoeic keratosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratoacanthoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Keratoacanthomas are rapidly growing squamoproliferative neoplasms that typically appear over a few weeks to months, which aligns with the three-week history in this case. They often occur in sun-exposed areas and are more common in individuals with a history of skin cancer, both of which are true for this patient. They have a central hyperkeratotic plug and may be erythematous or skin coloured.  Most keratoacanthomas will spontaneously resolve over a similar time period to their growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while keratoacanthoma is the most likely diagnosis based on the rapid growth and clinical presentation, a biopsy would typically be performed to definitively distinguish it from a squamous cell carcinoma. The management typically is surgical excision though rarely it may be observation alone.  Although many self-resolve, it is unusual to wait for it to resolve due to the difficulty in differentiating between other skin malignancies thus curettage or surgical removal is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential diagnosis for keratoacanthoma. Both are squamoproliferative growths, and it can be difficult to distinguish between them clinically. However, squamous cell carcinomas typically grow more slowly than the rapid growth seen in this case. Often, a biopsy is indicated to exclude malignant disease when a keratoacanthoma is suspected.  Nodular basal cell carcinoma or amelanotic melanoma should also be excluded for this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMerkel cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare type of skin cancer that can grow rapidly. However, it typically presents as a solitary, firm, red or purple nodule, often resembling a basal cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActinic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a pre-malignant keratinocyte lesion that appears on sun-damaged skin. While it can occur in similar locations to keratoacanthomas, actinic keratoses are typically small flat or slightly raised, scaly patches rather than rapidly growing nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrhoeic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign growth with a characteristic \u0022stuck-on\u0022 appearance. These lesions grow slowly over years and do not typically present as rapidly growing nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Keratoacanthoma is a rapidly enlarging squamoproliferative neoplasm that typically appears over a few weeks to months and often spontaneously resolves.","Keratoacanthoma can be difficult to distinguish clinically from squamous cell carcinoma, often requiring biopsy for definitive diagnosis.","Keratoacanthoma commonly occurs in sun-exposed areas and is associated with a history of skin cancer."],"references":["Kwiek B, Schwartz RA. Keratoacanthoma (KA): An update and review. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2016 Jun;74(6):1220-33. doi: 10.1016/j.jaad.2015.11.033. Epub 2016 Feb 4. PMID: 26853179.","Oakley A, Tan K, Keefe M, Mitchell G. Keratoacanthoma. Dermnet NZ. 2021.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/keratoacanthoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1354"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18809"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18809"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/552a3ca0-47ca-4a8b-b534-6b0a9658e12e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/552a3ca0-47ca-4a8b-b534-6b0a9658e12e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":411}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-08T22:10:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-08T22:11:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1354"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},